#compdef demoon
# ============================================================================
# demoon - Run Lua scripts in a Node-bridged sandbox (Node, MIT)
#
# Author : Eric Beje (ceifa)
# Upstream: https://github.com/ceifa/demoon
# npm    : demoon
#
# `demoon` is the author of wasmoon's *companion CLI* - a
# minimal "Lua + Node = demoon" runner that loads a `.lua`
# file, exposes the Node.js standard library to Lua via the
# wasmoon bridge, and lets the Lua code `require()` Node
# modules + JS files + sibling Lua modules transparently.
# The pitch: get Lua's syntax + ergonomics with Node's
# rich runtime + npm ecosystem.
#
# Sample features (from upstream README):
#   - require Node modules: `local http = require('http')`
#   - require JS files: `require('./mymodule.js')`
#   - require Lua files: `require('./mymod.lua')`
#   - top-level await: `mypromise:await()`
#   - async wrappers: `async(function (...) ... end)`
#   - Promise + setTimeout interop
#
# Usage:
#   demoon <entry.lua> [args...]
#
# All positional args after the entry file are passed to the
# Lua script as the `arg` global (1-indexed table). No CLI
# flags - everything is config-via-Lua-code.
#
# The wasmoon lane is built on `wasmoon 1.15.0` (declared
# verbatim at upstream package.json HEAD), the canonical
# Node Lua-VM library by Eric Beje (ceifa) - github.com/
# ceifa/wasmoon, 800+ stars. wasmoon compiles upstream
# PUC-Rio liblua (5.4 by default; 5.1 / 5.3 also available)
# to WebAssembly and ships it as a single `.wasm` binary
# loaded by a thin JS wrapper. The library runs in any Node
# version + every modern browser + Deno + Bun + Cloudflare
# Workers - the WebAssembly host abstraction is the
# universal denominator.
#
# Why Wasm-Lua over pure-JS-Lua (fengari-lua/fengari)? Two
# factors: (1) wasmoon's bytecode interpreter runs the
# unmodified PUC-Rio C code, so semantic conformance is
# byte-for-byte with the reference Lua (fengari, being a
# pure-JS reimplementation, occasionally diverges on
# corner cases). (2) wasmoon's interop layer
# (`lua.global.set('name', value)`) handles arbitrary JS
# value marshalling - functions, Promises, objects with
# property access proxies - more thoroughly than fengari's
# manual stack manipulation.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 239 :: Embedded Lua VM (host-language bindings to Lua scripting)
# Round 1417 :: TS-Node slot 3 of 4 :: CLOSES Axis 239 (232nd axis closed)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : mlua-rs/mlua                 [R1415 _maki]
#   Go      : yuin/gopher-lua              [R1416 _addon-controller]
#   TS/Node : ceifa/wasmoon                [R1417 THIS FILE]
#
# wasmoon closes Axis 239 with the *Wasm-loaded reference
# implementation* pattern. The three lanes form a clean
# spectrum of how-do-you-get-Lua-into-your-host-language:
#
#   - Rust (mlua): FFI bindings to natively-linked liblua
#     or LuaJIT - max performance, max platform-specific
#     build complexity
#   - Go (gopher-lua): pure-Go reimplementation - no liblua,
#     no CGo, preserves cross-compile; trades performance
#     for build simplicity
#   - Node (wasmoon): liblua compiled to Wasm + thin JS
#     wrapper - works in browser + every Node-flavor env,
#     trades minor cold-start vs JS-native (fengari) for
#     byte-for-byte conformance with PUC-Rio reference
#
# Cross-language interop happens at the Lua source level: a
# .lua file using only the standard library loads
# identically into mlua / gopher-lua / wasmoon. Host-bound
# Rust/Go/Node functions are per-lane non-portable. Lua
# 5.1 semantics are the lowest common denominator
# (gopher-lua targets 5.1 only); mlua + wasmoon support up
# to 5.4 + LuaJIT compatibility.
#
# Use-case spectrum:
#   - maki (Rust, mlua): plugin system for an AI coding
#     agent - load operator-authored Lua plugins that
#     extend tool registration + response post-processing
#   - addon-controller (Go, gopher-lua): K8s
#     ClusterProfile per-cluster value transformation
#     scripts at deploy time
#   - demoon (Node, wasmoon): standalone Lua runtime
#     using Node's stdlib as the host platform
#
# Three different operational shapes, one canonical Lua
# specification.
#
# Axis 239 closes the round 1417 cycle - 232nd axis closed
# total.
# ============================================================================

_demoon() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '1:Lua entry file:_files -g "*.lua"' \
        '*:script arguments:'
}

_demoon "$@"
